replies.bodyText:
ByteBuffer.duplicate does not make a copy of the data itself. It returns a new ByteBuffer instance pointing to the same backing buffer. The user may access the buffer's array (same with invoking .array()) but the point of invoking .duplicate() is for them not to mess with position, limit, etc.
This is the code in HeapByteBuffer.java:
   public ByteBuffer duplicate() {
        return new HeapByteBuffer(this.hb, this.markValue(), this.position(), this.limit(), this.capacity(), this.offset);
    }

